usjrforward: #OnTheGo

Jaguars prevail over Warriors in Cesafi Vball

The University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) Jaguars subdued the University of San Carlos (USC) Warriors, 3-1, in the Cesafi 23 Men’s Volleyball game at the USC Main Gymnasium on Monday, November 27.

In the opening set, the Jaguars showcased full control as they swamped the Warriors with consecutive attacks and blocks.

The Warriors attempted a comeback reducing the lead by three, 22-19. Despite their valiant efforts, their service errors led the Jaguars to secure the first set, 25-20.

In the middle of the second set, the momentum shifted as the Jaguars made service errors, allowing the Warriors to trail with a 10-point lead, 22-12, and earning their lone set win at 25-15.

The tension of the match reached its peak in the third set as both teams showcased resilience, tying at 13-13. However, the Jaguars survived their opponent, winning 25-23.

As the final set started, the Jaguars continued their momentum, narrowly clinching the victory, 28-25.

Moreover, Jaguars’ Head Coach Roldan Potot addressed the team’s weaknesses.

“Amo’ng blocking, especially amo’ng major blocker, amo pa jod ng i-work out this week or next game namo. Daghan pod kaayo’g service errors... sayang kaayo,” he explained.

The Jaguars remain undefeated at 6-0 and aim to sustain this against the Southwestern University (SWU) PHINMA Cobras on December 10, at the same venue.

via Khabzeel Clark Payao | FORWARD Probationary Writer

Photos Courtesy: Heron Augustus Flores | FORWARD Probationary Artist

text:
usjrforward: #OnTheGo

Lady Jaguars outclass Lady Webmasters in Cesafi Vball

The University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) Lady Jaguars sweeped the University of Cebu Lapu-Lapu and Mandaue (UCLM) Lady Webmasters, 3-0, in the Cesafi '23 Women's Volleyball game at the University of San Carlos (USC) Main Gymnasium on Monday, November 27.

Despite a shaky start marred by faulty services and receptions, the Lady Jaguars, led by Cesafi 22's Most Valuable Player (MVP) Louneth Marie Abangan, found their rhythm and executed powerful kills to secure a 25-13 win.

Carrying their momentum into the second set, the Lady Jaguars proved unstoppable, limiting the Lady Webmasters to just six points, 25-6.

In the final set, the Lady Jaguars weathered their opponents' attempts to regain their footing and ultimately sealed the victory at 25-13.

Meanwhile, Head Coach Roldan Potot expressed his confidence in the Lady Jaguars.

“Ga-expect jod ko nga three sets ra ni [nga game],” he said.

However, Potot acknowledged his hope for the team's performance.

“Mas mo ubos-ubos pa unta [ang UCLM] na score, kay attitude-wise, naa gihapon na siya nga kumpyansa during makadaog na. Dili na sila conscious sa mga errors, okay ra nila pero dapat dili jod ‘ta,” he added.

The Lady Jaguars will take on the Cebu Eastern College (CEC) Blue Dragons on Sunday, December 10, at the same venue.

via Krisha Faye Gascon | FORWARD Probationary Writer

Photos Courtesy: Narvie Klaryzze Borja | FORWARD Probationary Artist

usjrforward: #OnTheGo

Lady Jaguars claw Lady Dragons in Cesafi Vball

The Lady Jaguars of the University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) triumphed over the Cebu Eastern College (CEC) Lady Blue Dragons, 3-0, in the Cesafi '23 Women’s Volleyball game at the University of San Carlos (USC) Main Gymnasium on Sunday, November 26.

The Lady Jaguars breezed through the Lady Blue Dragons without a sweat, finishing a 25-7, 25-9, and 25-11 set scores.

The Jaguars’ opponents primarily gained points from their service errors or mistimed assists.

However, Jaguars’ Head Coach Roldan Potot explained there are still improvements to be made, especially on the team’s tendency to be complacent.

“I instructed them to let [the opponent] make their score, dili tungod sa among errors. Diha lang ko na-[worry] nila kay instead, ni-level man sila sa pikas. Diha ko medyo na disappointed,” Potot said.

Moreover, Potot reiterated his reminder to the team to remain grounded.

“I always remind them nga bisan kinsa among kontra nga team, dapat moduwa gyod mi sa among duwa. Medyo hinay pa ni among kontra, magkaanam og saka. Diri pa [lang] daan, [dapat] amo na i-polish,” he added.

The Lady Jaguars will face the University Of Cebu Lapu-Lapu and Mandaue (UCLM) Lady Webmasters on Thursday, November 30, at the same venue.

via Juan Enrique Reboquio | FORWARD Staff Writer

Photos Courtesy: Karina Adel Vestil | FORWARD Staff Artist

usjrforward: #OnTheGo

Jaguars suffer loss against Webmasters in Cesafi Fball

The University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) Jaguars faced a 0-2 loss to the University of Cebu (UC) Webmasters in their do-or-die Cesafi '23 Football match at the University of San Carlos (USC) Talamban Campus on Sunday, November 26.

The USJ-R Jaguars’ second loss could jeopardize their chance to play in the championship game should the UC Webmasters secure another victory against the University of the Philippines-Cebu (UPC) Maroons in their upcoming match.

In the early moments of their face-off, both the Jaguars and Webmasters encountered challenges in scoring due to mutually strong defenses and precise passes.

During the first half, spectators sat on the edge of their seats when Jaguars' Jay Cupas attempted a goal, only to fall short as the ball failed to touch the end zone.

The Webmasters then seized the lead and earned their first goal, leaving the Jaguars empty in the initial half.

The Jaguars regrouped in the second half with a more robust strategy against their opponents.

The tournament showcased both teams' offensive and defensive capabilities, resulting in a few on-field conflicts, including Jaguars' Mark Ian Vergara's collision with a Webmaster which followed a minor rash on his forehead.

The Webmasters earned their second goal in the final moments of the game, clinching a triumph over the Jaguars.

Meanwhile, Jaguars' Head Coach Joselito Bono kept a positive outlook despite their defeat, commending the players for their effort.

“Our players played well; they wanted to win. They wanted to play in the championship game, pero sayang,” Bono said.

In his final playing year, Jaguars' Team Captain and Goalkeeper Eugenn De Arce expressed pride in what could be his last game with the team.

“I’m proud ra gihapon sa among performance despite the result, kay nakita man gud nako ang pagpaningkamot sa mga players,” he said.

via Rufino Rico Jamisola | FORWARD Staff Writer

Photos Courtesy: Gabrielle Marie Paradiang | FORWARD Probationary Photographer

usjrforward: [JOSENIANS MOVING FORWARD]

Identity + Advocacy = Beauty
by Rey Martin Rio | FORWARD Staff Writer

In the dazzling world of beauty pageants, a queen stands out not only for her grace and elegance but also for her unwavering commitment to her advocacy—a passion for driving positive change.

Kristine Irish Mae “Kim” Mendoza, a third-year Bachelor of Science in Psychology student at the University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R), is a beauty queen, model, and LGBTQIA+ advocate.

Hailed as Miss Psychology 2023 on February 10 in the previous semester, she continues to make strides in shaping an empowered tomorrow.

Finding Her Spot on the Stage

From representing her Grade level to eventually debuting as a model for Palmolive Kids Shampoo, Kim discovered her love for performing and all things beauty at a young age.

Kim reflects on her humble beginning, sharing, “I barely even peeked out of my shell, but it all changed when I stepped onto the stage, starting with school events.”

Her journey evolved through joining off-campus pageants, fashion shows, and commercial gigs—even landing roles in a short film and a theatrical production.

“As I continue to build my portfolio, I never forget my roots, though. I still participate in school events and community productions,” Kim confides.

With pride, Kim acknowledges her growth and extends her gratefulness for every opportunity she had along the way.

“My beauty queen journey really requires passion, hard work, and determination—or what you call perseverance,” she adds.

On Identity and Representation

Amid the glamor and poise entailed in her life as a beauty queen, Kim equally strives to adamantly raise concern about important social issues.

As an advocate for LGBTQIA+ rights, Kim opens up about her personal struggle with identity.

“I grew up being confused about myself,” she admits.

Igniting her challenges of self-discovery, Kim saw pageantry as a powerful platform to inspire others and foster an accepting society, not just a tolerant one—true inclusivity.

For Kim, when discussing identity and representation within the pageant community, one needs to have “respect, empathy, and an open mind.”

“I found myself drawn to advocacy work, being a part of the [LGBTQIA+] community. I wanted to use my voice and my platform as a beauty queen to make a difference and help others feel seen, understood, and accepted,” she declares.

Sashaying with a Purpose

Kim wishes to impart to everyone, especially aspiring beauty queens, that we should all work towards becoming more compassionate individuals, highlighting fostering change within oneself before advocating for others.

“We should as well educate ourselves on issues that really matter to us [or] we are passionate about and seek out diverse perspectives to gain a better understanding of the complexities that surround us,” she expresses.

Kim encourages taking time to reflect on our beliefs and embody the values we hope to promote, saying, “Just remember that true beauty comes from within.”

Furthermore, Kim reminds us to remember that “advocating for social issues and creating positive changes is an ongoing process,” armed with the “willingness to learn and grow.”

Kim’s personal journey of mustering confidence serves as inspiration for those who believe in making an impact on the world, escaping the traditional narrative of beauty queens—a manifestation of the transformative power of embracing one's identity.

As Kim graces another stage moving forward, still with confidence and elegance, she leaves her word.

“By prioritizing our inner growth—self-improvement—we can truly make a positive impact on the world,” Kim says.

Visuals by Heron Augustus Flores | FORWARD Probationary Artist

usjrforward: #OnTheGo

Jaguars overtake Wildcats in final Cesafi 23 Basketball elims

The University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) Jaguars defeated the Cebu Institute of Technology-University (CIT-U) Wildcats, 77-63, in their final Cesafi 23 Men’s Basketball elimination match at the Cebu Coliseum on Sunday, November 26.

With over 5 minutes left on the game clock, USJ-R Jaguars’ Samuel Melicor earned the first score for the team as both were off to a slow opening quarter, 13-8.

The CIT-U Wildcats attempted a recovery with a point margin, 14-13, but Team Captain Jules Langres, Karl Malone Ventura, and Christian Sollano capitalized on their opponents’ weakening defense, ending the first half at 38-26.

Ventura, who chipped in 19 points for the team, poured in a series of treys in the third period which concluded with a 12-point gap (60-52).

Although they came alive during the final quarter by trimming the Jaguars’ point advantage to five, the Wildcats produced 11 points in their losing efforts.

Langres scored a total of 16 points and 17 rebounds, highlighted by two triples, as the Jaguars gained their seventh victory of the season. Milo Janao also contributed 11 points and 17 rebounds for the team.

Jaguars’ Head Coach Melo Banua commented on the team’s performance against the Wildcats.

“Gi-execute lang namo among gi-practice so far, pero na-down ang lamang by five [points]. Naa gihapo’y complacency,” Banua said.

Despite the Jaguars’ series of victories, the team’s spot in the semifinals is at stake as Cesafi officials investigate the eligibility of their player Evan Jose Agbong, particularly regarding his submitted records.

If Agbong’s records are deemed ineligible, the team’s chances of making it to the semifinals might be affected as appropriate sanctions determined by Cesafi will be imposed.

Cesafi officials have yet to announce their decision on Agbong and USJ-R’s status in the league.

Moreover, Banua shared that the Jaguars will keep on their practices regardless of the final decision.

“So far okay man among season [standing]. If tagaan mi og chance moduwa sa semis, we will prepare. Di gihapon mi moundang until next year. If tagaan mi og chance, maningkamot lang gyod mi,” he said.

Before the semifinals on December 5 and 7, the chosen Cesafi 23 players from the different member schools will participate in the All-Star Games to be held on Sunday, December 3, at the same venue.

The members of the All-Star Games’ teams are yet to be determined.

via Rey Martin Rio | FORWARD Staff Writer

Photos Courtesy: Christian Mananguite | FORWARD Staff Photographer

“So far okay man among season [standing]. If tagaan mi og chance moduwa sa semis, we will prepare. Di gihapon mi moundang until next year. If tagaan mi og chance, maningkamot lang gyod mi,” he said.

Before the semifinals on December 5 and 7, the chosen Cesafi 23 players from the different member schools will participate in the All-Star Games to be held on Sunday, December 3, at the same venue.

The members of the All-Star Games’ teams are yet to be determined.

via Rey Martin Rio | FORWARD Staff Writer

text:
usjrforward: #OnTheGo

Josenian grad clinches 5th spot in CELE 2023

Josenian alumna Analiza Mabini secured the fifth spot in the November 2023 Civil Engineers Licensure Examination (CELE) with a rating of 91.50% held on November 17-18, 2023.

Out of 18,582 examinees, the Professional Regulation Commission (PRC) officially declared that only 6,180 takers, or 33.26% successfully passed the licensure exam for civil engineers.

Mabini, a summa cum laude graduate of the Bachelor of Science in Civil Engineering program with a specialization in Structural Engineering, expressed that becoming a topnotcher was beyond her expectations and considers it a “miracle.”

“Truth be told, the exam was very hard for me. I even cried during the first night of our board exam,” she said.

Mabini shared that her whole review journey was the most challenging part, noting the need to study every day.

“Ang study kay would really take a toll on you, but you just believe in yourself jod. Never stop,” she stated.

Meanwhile, Mabini shared her way of lifting the exhaustion she felt on her journey.

“Mag-scroll na lang jod ko sa Facebook usahay if kapoy na jod kaayo, makigstorya ko sa akong ate kung unsa among mga kaagi pag childhood,” she said.

Mabini added that the time she spent talking with her friends was what she considered the “silver lining” during her review period, which she described as her “dark time.”

Mabini also parted advice to engineering students and aspiring engineers who are preparing for the licensure exam.

“Absorb everything that you will learn in the classroom because it would really help you in your review days…Study hard, aim high, [and] believe in yourself because there would be many times that you would doubt yourself,” she said.

During the press conference held at the University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) yesterday, November 25, the Dean of the School of Engineering, Dr. Dennis Kilongkilong, stated that the last time USJ-R had a topnotcher in the field of civil engineering was in 2019.

“We produced 22 new civil engineers for the School of Engineering in USJ-R and this is not a one-man show. It is a collaborative effort [between] the team Civil Engineering Department and the faculty and staff,” Kilongkilong said.

According to the USJ-R Vice President for Academics & Research, Rev. Fr. Jose Alden Alipin, OAR, Mabini will receive P75,000 and a brand new laptop as a reward.

via Trixcy Clar | FORWARD Staff Writer

Photos Courtesy: Ejay Villaver | FORWARD Staff Writer

text:
usjrforward: #OnTheGo

JBEES conducts acquaintance party ‘23

The University of San Jose-Recoletos Junior Business Executives and Entrepreneurs Society (USJ-R JBEES) hosted an acquaintance party with the theme, ”Golden Allure: An Evening of White and Gold Enchantment” at the Sugbutel Family Hotel on Saturday evening, November 25.

The event aimed to foster camaraderie and future collaborations among students under the degree programs of the Bachelor of Science in Business Administration major in Operations Management (BSBA OM) and Bachelor of Science in Entrepreneurship (BSE).

Despite facing obstacles, JBEES Vice President-External Lyndon Orcullo shared that he is satisfied with the successful execution of the long-awaited event.

Orcullo further stressed out the experience by saying that it is ”hard yet fulfilling.”

The program featured a runway showcasing members of the organization in their white and gold outfits, followed by a communal dinner.

Subsequently, engaging games served as ice-breakers for the guests, along with an intermission number by JBEESians under the class of Professor Francisco Gatdula serenading the crowd with their rendition of Christmas songs.

Meanwhile, JBEES President, Jehallel Enriquez, expressed his gratefulness for the success of the acquaintance party and was delighted with its conclusion.

Enriquez emphasized that the event is just the start of building connections between the students in the long run.

”We do hope that we’re gonna see more connections even with the students in the future events,” he added.

The event hailed Ethan Paul Pablo and Maxene Joson, the King and Queen of the Night, respectively.

via Louise Lambiquit | FORWARD Probationary Writer

Photos Courtesy: Khen Fernandez | FORWARD Probationary Artist
